title: For Sale/Trade:  Benelli M3 Tactical shotgun, used, pump/semi-auto selectable, rare top-folding stock
postcontent:
For sale, Benelli M3 with folding stock, used, in very good condition. 

This an Italian manufactured tactical shotgun, as used by Czech special forces, Canadian anti-terror forces, Indonesia's KOPASKA force, Luxembourg's Police Counter Terrorism units, and others. It features a unique semi-auto or pump selectable action (useful for switching from buckshot defense rounds to specialty ammo that can't cycle the action, like tear gas or taser rounds). Benelli's semi-autos are world renowned for their speed and durability, and it holds true for the M3. 

It has a cylinder bore 18 1/2" barrel. This one has the rare top-folding rear should stock which doubles as a carrying handle. Pistol grip. Sling, tactical case, and manual are included. Front grip plastic is worn around assembly nuts, see last pic. Firearm condition is "very good"... some finish wear on moving parts, but rest of finish is like new. 

Works fantastic, I'm just selling to fund other toys.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mannlicher style Mauser Sporter in 243.
postcontent: I have a rifle that started life as a German Mauser, WWII vintage, but was rebuilt into a sporting rifle after being brought back to the states. As you can see from the pics it was tastefully reworked with attention to detail and craftsmanship. The barrel is approximately 19 inches long, and looks awesome with the ful length stock. It is drilled and tapped for scope mounts, I got it with the mounts still attached and simply put the rings and scope on. The scope is a 1970's vintage Weaver 2.5-7x32 Wide field or "TV View". Do some research on these and you'll see that they regularly sell for what new scopes do because they work so well. If you're wondering why I set my price where I did, do some research. ANY sporterized Mauser will sell for $250-300. This one has been rebarreled, restocked, bedded, and had a new safety and trigger installed. A very well done Guild Mauser sporter can run a couple of grand. This is a former military gun, very well sporterized with an great, vintage original Weaver on it. If you were to do something like this yourself, you'd be out well north of $1000, and that's without a decent Mauser to start with! This rifle is ready to hunt as is, grab it now and kill a deer Saturday!

title: For Sale:  SIG SAUER P6 9MM W. German Military Pistol OFF-LIST
location: South Bay L.A., Torrance, Redondo Beach, Los Angeles, California
postcontent:
Military & police version of the P225, 9mm double-action/single-action with a safety-decock that any modern SIG owner will fast recognize. 

This 9x19mm M&P pistol shows SOME wear.  I'm no expert but would rate it at 90%. 
It's in good used condition, with two 8 round magazines, black composite handgrip, black alloy frame, black/blued steel slide. 

  West German issued Swiss SIG SAUER P6 9mm, their military and police version of the P225, manafactured to the "P" standards of the Republic.    You can tell commercial models from cop guns by the "P6" marking, four-digit born-on date, and funky little Deformationssporn hooked hammer.  Each of the states in Germany had its own police force known as the Landespolizei (State Police) and they, along with the Federal Police and municipal police forces were allowed to select any of the approved ‘P’ guns to arm their officers. 
  Switzerland’s SIG works had previously sold the Germans a small number of P2s, and introduced their new P225 pistol to replace stocks of Walther P1s in 1975. 
  They collaborated with J. P. Sauer & Sohn, a local German company, to make a bid. This led to the beautiful relationship that became SIG-Sauer while the gun this union created was adopted as the P6. 
  Some 40,000 of these handguns were made at Sauer’s factory in Eckenförde, Germany, making it one of the most popular Teutonic police pistols of the 1980s. 

I've heard some P6 owners say that they easily added Sig Pro night sights that popped right on with the assistance of a sight pusher.
How does it shoot? Say what you will, but like many of my other pieces, I've never had the time to take it to the range. That's what living in L.A. can do to you. Still I like it by itself, just as a piece of history. 

Double-action/single-action, with decocker. Serial # XX, in the original blue plastic Sig Sauer box it came in as shipped from Century Arms years ago. 

FTF deal for a local buyer, we can set up a meet in the South Bay L.A. Redondo Beach & adjacent area. If you're in the area feel free to contact me and check it out.
